%N A391966 Smallest integer k greater than 1 such that every solution of y^m = y (for all integers m > 1) in the commutative ring of n-adic integers is also a solution of y^k = y.
%C A391966 Let Z_n denote the ring of n-adic integers (inverse limit of Z/(n^k) Z, k -> infinity).
%C A391966 Solving the equation y^a(n) = y in the commutative ring of n-adic integers Z_n arises when we need to provide a closed formula for the constant congruence speed in the radix-n numeral system as n > 1 is a nonprime squarefree integer (e.g., finding the 9 solutions y^3 = y in Z_6 or the 15 solutions y^5 = y in Z_10).
%C A391966 A390915(n) gives the exact number of solutions (including 0) of y^a(n) = y in Z_n.
%C A391966 For all n < 35, a(n) = A076566(n-1), but then we have 13 = a(35) <> A076566(34) = 7.
%C A391966 In general, a(n) <> A076566(n-1) occurs infinitely many times, by construction (since A076566 depends on a single prime factor, whereas a(n) involves all odd prime divisors of rad(n)).
%C A391966 Let p_j be prime numbers such that rad(n) := p_1*p_2*...*p_{omega(n)} denotes the product of all distinct prime factors of n. Then a(n) = 3 if rad(n) = 2; otherwise a(n) = 1 + lcm(p_j - 1 : 1 <= j <= omega(n), p_j <> 2).
%C A391966 In particular, for infinitely many n, the ratio A390915(n)/a(n) can be made arbitrarily large (e.g., n = 30 is the smallest n such that A390915(n)/a(n) >= 9).
%H A391966 Gérard P. Michon, <a href="http://www.numericana.com/answer/p-adic.htm#integers">Introduction to p-adic integers</a>, Numericana.
%H A391966 Marco Ripà, <a href="https://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.18023891">Solving the Fundamental Equation y^(tau(r)) = y in Z_r</a>, Zenodo, 2025.
%H A391966 Marco Ripà and Gabriele Di Pietro, <a href="https://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.15276824">A Compact Notation for Peculiar Properties Characterizing Integer Tetration</a>, Zenodo, 2025.
%F A391966 a(n) = 3 if rad(n) = 2; otherwise a(n) = 1 + lcm(p - 1 : p divides rad(n), p <> 2).
%e A391966 a(10) = 5 (since y^5 = y admits all 15 solutions in Z_10 arising from y^k = y for integers k > 1).
%o A391966 (Python)
%o A391966 from math import lcm
%o A391966 from sympy import primefactors, prod
%o A391966 def rad(n):
%o A391966     return 1 if n < 2 else prod(primefactors(n))
%o A391966 def a(n):
%o A391966     r = rad(n)
%o A391966     if r == 2:
%o A391966         return 3
%o A391966     L = 1
%o A391966     for p in primefactors(r):
%o A391966         if p != 2:
%o A391966             L = lcm(L, p-1)
%o A391966     return L+1
%o A391966 print([a(n) for n in range(2,78)])
